title: Dipper specimen at Macedonia, Iowa
contributing_institution: Iowa State University. Special Collections and University Archives
description: Draft article. Article written by George Hendrickson discusses Philip DuMont's examination of the Stempel collection and seeks to establish the Dipper as an accidental bird in Iowa. Published in Iowa Bird Life vol. 27, no. 3. This article describes the specimen discussed in: https://n2t.net/ark:/87292/w9z31nn75, https://n2t.net/ark:/87292/w9b56d43m, and https://n2t.net/ark:/87292/w94f1mh9x. The American Dipper described in this article was reviewed by the Iowa Ornithologists' Union Records Committee: https://n2t.net/ark:/87292/w9930nz0j.
subject: Rare birds;Zoological specimens;American Dipper (Cinclus mexicanus)

title: Philip DuMont letter to George Hendrickson regarding editorial changes to the revised checklist, November 29, 1956
contributing_institution: Iowa State University. Special Collections and University Archives
description: Letter from Philip DuMont to George Hendrickson dated November 29, 1956. In this letter to George Hendrickson (copied to Martin Grant and Harold Ennis) DuMont details some changes that he made to the revised checklist and notes that he had Fred Lincoln, who is in the process of reviewing the American Ornithologists' Union checklist, double check his corrections. Included is Philip DuMont's edited revised Check-list of Iowa Birds. This document is in response to a letter from Hendrickson: https://n2t.net/ark:/87292/w9w08wg2d.

title: Philip DuMont letter to Max Stempel regarding records for the Stempel collection, November 9, 1934
contributing_institution: Iowa State University. Special Collections and University Archives
description: Letter from Philip DuMont to Max Stempel dated November 9, 1934. DuMont thanks Stempel for allowing him to view the collection and returns some of Guido Stempel's notes that he had accidentally walked off with. DuMont encourages Stempel to label the birds and asks for some additional information in the hopes of being able to publish about the collection. This document is answered by a letter from Stempel: https://n2t.net/ark:/87292/w9gx44t6s.

title: Philip DuMont letter to Thomas Stephens regarding questionable birds in the Revised List of Iowa Birds, January 30, 1934
contributing_institution: Iowa State University. Special Collections and University Archives
description: Letter from Philip DuMont to Thomas Stephens dated January 30, 1934. In this letter DuMont suggests printing an Iowa ornithology bibliography for members of the Iowa Ornithologists' Union, discusses why some birds were included or excluded from his book "Revised List of the Birds of Iowa," and says he will be looking for more samples and sight records in preparation for issuing a new edition of the book. This document is in response to a letter from Thomas Stephens: https://n2t.net/ark:/87292/w9cv4br39.

title: Philip DuMont letter to Hugo Schroeder regarding nesting birds in Iowa, January 10, 1935
contributing_institution: Iowa State University. Special Collections and University Archives
description: Letter from Philip DuMont to Hugo Schroeder dated January 10, 1935. In this letter DuMont thanks Schroeder for notes about nesting birds in Iowa and informs him that the information will be used for the revised edition of the "Revised List of the Birds of Iowa." title: Questionnaire for a new birds of Iowa, Oscar Allert
contributing_institution: Iowa State University. Special Collections and University Archives
description: Annotated checklist of birds. Oscar Allert responds to Philip DuMont's questionnaire requesting specimens and sight records needed for his revised list of the birds of Iowa. Allert reports on whether the species is present, if it breeds in state, how common or rare the bird is, and if there is a specimen available.
subject: Birds--Geographical distribution;Birds--Nests;Birds--Research;Rare birds

title: Helen King letter to Philip DuMont regarding Starlings in Grundy County, December 11, 1933

title: List of bird sighted in Boone County on May 14, 1933
contributing_institution: Iowa State University. Special Collections and University Archives
description: Undated research notes. This is a list of birds sighted in Boone County on May 14, 1933 between 5:00 a.m. and 7:00 p.m. by Walter Rosene, Sr., Robert Walker, and Walter Rosene, Jr. The sighting of 124 species of birds in single day by a single observer or party of observers is believed to be a record for Iowa. title: Questionnaire for a new birds of Iowa, Walter Rosene
contributing_institution: Iowa State University. Special Collections and University Archives
description: Annotated checklist of birds. Walter Rosene responds to Philip DuMont's questionnaire requesting specimens and sight records needed for his revised list of the birds of Iowa. Rosene reports on whether the species is present, if it breeds in state, how common or rare the bird is, and if there is a specimen available.
subject: Birds--Geographical distribution;Birds--Nests;Birds--Research;Rare birds

description: Draft article. Contains summary results for the Des Moines Audubon Society Christmas bird count held December 26 1934. These results were included in the article "Christmas bird censuses from Iowa" published in Bird-Lore, vol. 37, no. 1.
subject: Bird watching;Birds--Counting;Weather

title: Biological abstracts: Red-tailed Hawk
contributing_institution: Iowa State University. Special Collections and University Archives
description: Draft article. In this article Philip DuMont discusses Hawks in Iowa, focusing on the Red-tailed Hawk and its subspecies. Published in Biological Abstracts, 1933.
subject: Birds--Geographical distribution;Birds--Identification;Rough-legged Hawk (Buteo lagopus);Red-tailed Hawk (Buteo jamaicensis);Swainson's Hawk (Buteo swainsoni)

title: Woodcocks increasing in numbers
contributing_institution: Iowa State University. Special Collections and University Archives
description: Press release dated January 31, 1935. In this Outdoor Iowa news release from the Iowa Fish and Game Commission Philip DuMont notes that a recent study by Olin Sewall Pettingill indicates that the Woodcock is rebounding nicely in Iowa since its recent protection.
subject: Bird populations;Birds--Geographical distribution;Wildlife conservation;American Woodcock (Scolopax minor)

title: The Revised list of the Birds of Iowa (part 1)
contributing_institution: Iowa State University. Special Collections and University Archives
description: Manuscript dated February 1, 1934. This is an edited manuscript for the revised edition of the book "The Revised list of the birds of Iowa" published by the University of Iowa and issued as University of Iowa studies in natural history, vol. 15, no. 5. This work lists all the bird species known to have occurred in Iowa. This item ends on manuscript page 92.
subject: Bird watching;Guidebooks;Birds--Geographical distribution;Ornithology--Methodology

title: Why keep bird records?
contributing_institution: Iowa State University. Special Collections and University Archives
description: Lecture notes presented May 10, 1947. Includes the paper "The Use of bird records." title: James Peters letter to Philip DuMont regarding Sparrow identification, January 2, 1934
contributing_institution: Iowa State University. Special Collections and University Archives
description: Letter from James Peters to Philip DuMont dated January 2, 1934. Peters informs Philip DuMont that he has not finished reviewing the Sparrow specimens sent to him, but gives a preliminary assessment. Included with this letter is a letter from Janetta DuMont, who is forwarding Philip DuMont's mail, discussing the DuMont family's activities around Christmas. This document is in response to a letter from DuMont: https://n2t.net/ark:/87292/w9n00zs9f. This document is answered by a letter from DuMont: https://n2t.net/ark:/87292/w97m04048.
subject: Bird watching;Birds--Identification;Ornithology--Study and teaching;Classification;Zoological specimens;Families;Grasshopper Sparrow (Ammodramus savannarum);Savannah Sparrow (Passerculus sandwichensis)

title: The Revised list of the Birds of Iowa (part 3)
contributing_institution: Iowa State University. Special Collections and University Archives
description: Continuation of a manuscript dated February 1, 1934. This is an edited manuscript for the revised edition of the book "The Revised list of the birds of Iowa" published by the University of Iowa and issued as University of Iowa studies in natural history, vol. 15, no. 5. This work lists all the bird species known to have occurred in Iowa. This item begins on manuscript page 239 and ends on manuscript page 328.

title: Subspecies, and their place in the list of Iowa Birds
contributing_institution: Iowa State University. Special Collections and University Archives
description: Lecture notes delivered May 5, 1933. Notes for a presentation given by Philip DuMont during the 1933 annual meeting of the Iowa Ornithologists' Union discusses that while some ornithologists may be interested in subspecies, field notes should only record the species since determining a subspecies in the field is not reliable and should be only undertaken by the close study of collected specimens.
